Trust in PBS

Christopher Ali, Hilde Van den Bulck, Jonathan Kropko

2023-08-25

1 Abstract

This contribution explores the how and why of trust in PBS. After this introduction, we sketch the constitutive characteristics of PBS. Next, we theoretically explore the notion of trust in general and with regards to media in particular, resulting in a set of more specific research questions. Subsequently, we discuss the methodological set up. We explored US audiences trust in PBS by means of a survey questionnaire. Next, we discuss the results, focusing on institutional aspects, on characteristics of the offerings and performance of PBS and on the role of long-standing relationships between PBS and its audiences. Finally, we discuss the implications of our understanding of what constitutes trust in PBS for the institution and for government policy towards PBS in an age of distrust in media and society.

3.1 Characteristics of trustee

Institution-based trust is impersonal and based on the conviction that society provides structures (regulations, institutions) that allow people to trust those structures and, through that, each other. As McKnight & Chervany (2013) explain, this comes with a structural assurance: structures have built-in guarantees that ensure trusting intentions.

Characteristics of PBS as trusted institution:

  • R1: How and in what ways is trust in PBS based in its institutional / structural characteristics (funding, independence)

pbs_trust <- select(pbs, starts_with("personaltrust")) %>%
  rename("NPR"="personaltrust_npr",
         "NASA"="personaltrust_nasa",                
         "Smithsonian"="personaltrust_smithsonian",
         "PBS"="personaltrust_pbs",
         "Public Schools"="personaltrust_publicschools",
         "Congress"="personaltrust_congress",
         "Current President"="personaltrust_currentpresident",
         "State Government"="personaltrust_stategovernment",
         "Postal Services"="personaltrust_postalservices",
         "Courts of Law"="personaltrust_courtsoflaw",         
         "Law Enforcement and Police"="personaltrust_lawenforcementpolice",
         "Military"="personaltrust_military") %>%
  pivot_longer(c("NPR","NASA","Smithsonian","PBS","Public Schools",
               "Congress","Current President","State Government",
               "Postal Services","Courts of Law","Law Enforcement and Police","Military"),
               names_to = "institution",
               values_to = "trust") %>%
  group_by(institution, trust) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(trust = fct_relevel(trust, "No opinion","Distrust a great deal",
                             "Somewhat distrust", "Neither trust nor distrust",
                             "Somewhat trust", "Trust a great deal"),
         institution = relevel(as.factor(institution),ref="PBS")) %>%
  na.omit()

  • Process-based trust results from repeated contact and interaction between trustor and trustee. While the original contact and interaction may be coincidental (stumbling upon a particular media channel), repeated contacts can result in the reduction of uncertainty and the building of trust. Translated into how long folks have been PBS viewers (Mr Rogers effect)
pbs_whytrust <- select(pbs, open_whyyoutrust, personaltrust_pbs) %>%
  mutate(most_trust = (personaltrust_pbs == 'Trust a great deal')) %>%
  group_by(open_whyyoutrust) %>%
  summarize(frequency = n(),
            most_trust = round(100*mean(most_trust), 1)) %>%
  arrange(-frequency)
